{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"201"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/201"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.35,0.49,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60384"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/201"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45809"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3813"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9119"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40471"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60384"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man is admitted to hospital with a three-month history of increasing constipation and 10 kg weight loss. Over the last two days he has had absolute constipation and abdominal distension. His medical history includes hypertension and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His respiratory symptoms are such that he is unable to climb a flight of stairs. He takes perindopril and a long-acting bronchodilator. He is a reformed smoker with a 40 pack-year history and drinks two glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is grossly distended with tinkling bowel sounds. A CT scan confirms a stenosing tumour at the rectosigmoid junction, with proximally distended loops of colon. In addition, tumour deposits are visible in the omentum, there is some ascites and a left hydronephrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defunctioning loop colostomy","Stent insertion","Tumour resection and end colostomy (Hartmann procedure)","Tumour resection and primary anastomosis","Defunctioning loop ileostomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with malignant large bowel obstruction from metastatic colorectal cancer, complicated by poor performance status and significant respiratory comorbidity. The management approach should focus on palliation while minimising procedural risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStent insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management option as it provides effective palliation of the obstruction with minimal procedural risk. Colonic stents can be inserted under sedation rather than general anaesthesia, have a technical success rate of over 90%, and allow patients to return home quickly. They avoid the morbidity associated with surgery and stoma care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefunctioning loop colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E would relieve the obstruction but requires general anaesthesia and has higher morbidity than stenting. It also creates a permanent stoma which impacts quality of life. While it may be considered if stenting fails, it should not be first-line in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour resection and end colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E (Hartmann\u0027s procedure) represents major surgery with significant morbidity and mortality risk, particularly given this patient\u0027s poor respiratory function. With metastatic disease, such extensive surgery is not justified for purely palliative purposes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour resection and primary anastomosis\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for potentially curative treatment in a fit patient with localised disease. However, this patient has metastatic disease and poor performance status, making this option inappropriately aggressive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefunctioning loop ileostomy\u003C/strong\u003E would not adequately decompress the obstructed colon as it is proximal to the obstruction. It would also require general anaesthesia and create a high-output stoma which can be difficult to manage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principles in managing this case are to achieve effective palliation while minimising procedural risk and impact on quality of life. Colonic stenting best achieves these goals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Colonic stents offer good palliation for poor surgical risk patients with malignant colonic obstruction.","Surgical intervention carries higher morbidity and mortality in patients with advanced disease and poor performance status.","The presence of metastatic disease and significant comorbidities should guide management towards palliative rather than curative options."],"references":["Bromham N. Colorectal cancer: summary of NICE guidance. BMJ 2020; 368:m461."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"201"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-12T09:43:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-10T18:34:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"201"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60384"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":